[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:wxwidgets/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] In software design, the **look and feel** of a graphical user interface comprises aspects of its design, including elements such as colors, shapes, layout, and typefaces (the "look"), as well as the behavior of dynamic elements such as buttons, boxes, and menus (the "feel").
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] The term can also refer to aspects of a non-graphical user interface (such as a command-line interface), as well as to aspects of an API – mostly to parts of an API that are not related to its functional properties.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] The term is used in reference to both software and websites.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] Look and feel applies to other products.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] In documentation, for example, it refers to the graphical layout (document size, color, font, etc.) and the writing style.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] In the context of equipment, it refers to consistency in controls and displays across a product line.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] Look and feel in operating system user interfaces serves two general purposes.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] First, it provides branding, helping to identify a set of products from one company.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] Second, it increases ease of use, since users will become familiar with how one product functions (looks, reads, etc.) and can translate their experience to other products with the same look and feel.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] Contrary to operating system user interfaces, for which look and feel is a part of the product identification, widget toolkits often allow users to specialize their application look and feel, by deriving the default look and feel of the toolkit, or by completely defining their own.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] This specialization can go from skinning (that only deals with the look, or visual appearance of the graphical control elements) to completely specializing the way the user interacts with the software (that is, the feel).
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] The definition of the look and feel to associate with the application is often done at initialization, but some Widget toolkits, such as the Swing widget toolkit that is part of the Java API, allow users to change the look and feel at runtime (see Pluggable look and feel).
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] Some companies try to assert copyright of trade dress over their look and feel.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] Unison* (1986) case was an early software copyright case that attempted to apply U.S. copyright law to the look and feel presented by a software product.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] In 1987 Lotus Development sued Paperback Software and Mosaic for copyright infringement, false and misleading advertising, and unfair competition over their low-cost clones of 1-2-3, VP Planner and Twin, and sued Borland over its Quattro spreadsheet.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] Dealers reported that sales of the clones increased because of publicity from the lawsuit.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] In December 1989, Xerox sued Apple over the Macintosh copyright.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] Apple Computer was notable for its use of the term *look and feel* in reference to their Mac OS operating system.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] The firm tried, with some success, to block other software developers from creating software that had a similar look and feel.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] Apple argued that they had a copyright claim on the look and feel of their software, and even went so far as to sue Microsoft, alleging that the Windows operating system was illegally copying their look and feel.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] ADAPSO could not come to a consensus on look and feel.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] The trade association's software products board of directors concluded that copyright should not protect look and feel.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] The software protection committee was so divided, however, that when Lotus's general counsel recused himself as chairman from a February 1987 meeting on the subject, the committee could not choose a replacement.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] Although provoking a vehement reaction from some in the software community, and causing Richard Stallman to form the League for Programming Freedom, the expected landmark ruling never happened, as most of the issues were resolved based on a license that Apple had granted Microsoft for Windows 1.0.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] The First Circuit Court of Appeals rejected a copyright claim on the feel of a user interface in *Lotus v.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] In 2012 and 2014, Apple Inc. filed lawsuits against competing manufacturers of smartphones and tablet computers, claiming that those manufacturers copied the look and feel of Apple's popular iPhone and iPad products.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] An API, which is an interface to software which provides some sort of functionality, can also have a certain look and feel.
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] Different parts of an API (e.g. different classes or packages) are often linked by common syntactic and semantic conventions (e.g. by the same asynchronous execution model, or by the same way object attributes are accessed).
[src:wxwidgets/look-and-feel] These elements are rendered either explicitly (i.e. are part of the syntax of the API), or implicitly (i.e. are part of the semantics of the API).
[src:wxwidgets/native-computing] Native software is built to be executed directly by processors that implement a compatible instruction set.
[src:wxwidgets/native-computing] A program that runs natively on one platform is runnable on another platform via an emulator if an emulator is available and, generally, with significant runtime speed degradation.
[src:wxwidgets/native-computing] For example, games for a Game Boy (typically distributed as a cartridge), generally run natively on a Game Boy which is relatively incompatible with other computer platforms.
[src:wxwidgets/native-computing] To run such a game on another processor, software that emulates the Game Boy hardware is required.
[src:wxwidgets/native-computing] Cross-platform software can run on multiple processors although possibly requiring it to be re-built for different target systems.
[src:wxwidgets/native-computing] A native application programming interface (API) provides direct access to an underlying technology.
[src:wxwidgets/native-computing] For example, the Windows Native API is an application programming interface specific for the Windows NT kernel, which provides access to some kernel functions which cannot be directly accessed through the more universal Windows API.
[src:wxwidgets/native-computing] A native virtual machine (VM) runs directly on hardware, without virtualization or virtualization at its lowest level.
[src:wxwidgets/native-computing] For example, with multiple levels of virtualization, the lowest level operating system – the one that actually maintains direct control of the hardware – is referred to as a "Native VM".
[src:wxwidgets/native-computing] Applied to data, native data formats or communication protocols are those supported by a certain computer hardware or software, with maximal consistency and minimal amount of additional components.
[src:wxwidgets/native-computing] For example, EGA and VGA video adapters *natively* support code page 437.
[src:wxwidgets/native-computing] This does not preclude supporting other code pages, but it requires either a font uploading or using graphic modes.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] A **software framework** is software that provides reusable, generic functionality which developers can extend or customize to create complete solutions.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] It offers an abstraction layer over lower-level code and infrastructure, allowing developers to focus on implementing business logic rather than building common functionality from scratch.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] Generally, a framework is intended to enhance productivity by allowing developers to focus on satisfying business requirements rather than reimplementing generic functionality.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] Frameworks often include support programs, compilers, software development kits, code libraries, toolsets, and APIs that integrate various components within a larger software platform or environment.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] Unlike a library, where user code controls the program's control flow, a framework implements inversion of control by dictating the overall structure and calling user code at predefined extension points (e.g., through template methods or hooks).
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] Frameworks also provide default behaviours that work out-of-the-box, structured mechanisms for extensibility, and a fixed core that accepts extensions (e.g., plugins or subclasses) without direct modification.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] A framework differs from an application that can be extended—such as a web browser via an extension or a video game via a mod—in that it is intentionally incomplete scaffolding designed to be completed through its extension points while following specific architectural patterns.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] For example, a team using a web framework to develop a banking website can focus on writing banking business logic rather than handling low-level details like web request processing or state management.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] According to Pree, software frameworks consist of *frozen spots* and *hot spots*.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] *Frozen spots* define the overall architecture of a software system, that is to say its basic components and the relationships between them.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] These remain unchanged (frozen) in any instantiation of the application framework.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] *Hot spots* represent the parts where the programmers using the framework add their own code to add the functionality specific to their own project.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] The necessary functionality can be implemented by using the Template Method Pattern in which the *frozen spots* are known as invariant methods and the *hot spots* are known as variant or hook methods.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] The invariant methods in the superclass provide default behaviour while the hook methods in each subclass provide custom behaviour.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] When developing a concrete software system with a software framework, developers utilize the hot spots according to the specific needs and requirements of the system.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] Software frameworks rely on the Hollywood Principle: "Don't call us, we'll call you." This means that the user-defined classes (for example, new subclasses) receive messages from the predefined framework classes.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] Developers usually handle this by implementing superclass abstract methods.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] One potential downside of using a framework is that it adds to the size of a program, a phenomenon termed code bloat.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] This can be exacerbated by using multiple, sometimes competing, frameworks in the same codebase.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] Learning how to use a framework can be substantial.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] The intended efficiencies of using the framework may be outweighed by the cost to learn it, especially for a framework that is new to the development staff.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] However, once a framework is learned, development team speed may increase for future work.
[src:wxwidgets/software-framework] Some claim that the most effective frameworks evolve from re-factoring an existing solution, such as a generic one-size-fits-all framework developed by third parties for general purposes, rather than from green-field development.
[src:wxwidgets/widget-toolkit] A **widget toolkit**, **widget library**, **GUI toolkit**, **GUI framework**, **UI framework**, or **UX library** is a library or a collection of libraries containing a set of graphical control elements (called *widgets*) used to construct the graphical user interface (GUI) of programs.
[src:wxwidgets/widget-toolkit] Most widget toolkits additionally include their own rendering engine.
[src:wxwidgets/widget-toolkit] This engine can be specific to a certain operating system or windowing system or contain back-ends to interface with multiple ones and also with rendering APIs such as OpenGL, OpenVG, or EGL.
[src:wxwidgets/widget-toolkit] The look and feel of the graphical control elements can be hard-coded or decoupled, allowing the graphical control elements to be themed/skinned.
[src:wxwidgets/widget-toolkit] Some toolkits may be used from other languages by employing language bindings.
[src:wxwidgets/widget-toolkit] Graphical user interface builders such as e.g.
[src:wxwidgets/widget-toolkit] Glade Interface Designer facilitate the authoring of GUIs in a WYSIWYG manner employing a user interface markup language such as in this case GtkBuilder.
[src:wxwidgets/widget-toolkit] The GUI of a program is commonly constructed in a cascading manner, with graphical control elements being added directly to on top of one another.
[src:wxwidgets/widget-toolkit] Most widget toolkits use event-driven programming as a model for interaction.
[src:wxwidgets/widget-toolkit] The toolkit handles user events, for example when the user clicks on a button.
[src:wxwidgets/widget-toolkit] When an event is detected, it is passed on to the application where it is dealt with.
[src:wxwidgets/widget-toolkit] The design of those toolkits has been criticized for promoting an oversimplified model of event-action, leading programmers to create error-prone, difficult to extend and excessively complex application code.
[src:wxwidgets/widget-toolkit] Finite-state machines and hierarchical state machines have been proposed as high-level models to represent the interactive state changes for reactive programs.
[src:wxwidgets/widget-toolkit] A window is considered to be a graphical control element.
[src:wxwidgets/widget-toolkit] In some windowing systems, windows are added directly to the scene graph (canvas) by the window manager, and can be stacked and layered on top of each other through various means.
[src:wxwidgets/widget-toolkit] Each window is associated with a particular application which controls the widgets added to its canvas, which can be watched and modified by their associated applications.
[src:wxwidgets/wxwidgets] The project was started under the name wxWindows in 1992 by Julian Smart at the University of Edinburgh.
[src:wxwidgets/wxwidgets] The project was renamed wxWidgets in 2004 in response to a trademark claim by Microsoft UK.
[src:wxwidgets/wxwidgets] It is free and open source software, distributed under the terms of the wxWidgets Licence, which satisfies those who wish to produce for GPL and proprietary software.
[src:wxwidgets/wxwidgets] wxWidgets covers systems such as Microsoft Windows, macOS (Carbon and Cocoa), iOS (Cocoa Touch), Linux/Unix (X11, Motif, and GTK), OpenVMS, OS/2 and AmigaOS.
[src:wxwidgets/wxwidgets] A version for embedded systems is under development.
[src:wxwidgets/wxwidgets] wxWidgets is used across various industry sectors, most notably by Xerox, Advanced Micro Devices (AMD), Lockheed Martin, NASA and the Center for Naval Analyses.
[src:wxwidgets/wxwidgets] It is also used in the public sector and education by, for example, Dartmouth Medical School, National Human Genome Research Institute, National Center for Biotechnology Information, and many others. wxWidgets is used in many open source projects, and by individual developers.
[src:wxwidgets/wxwidgets] wxWidgets (initially wxWindows; "w" is for Windows, and "x" is for X Window System) was started in 1992 by Julian Smart at the University of Edinburgh.
[src:wxwidgets/wxwidgets] He attained an honours degree in Computational science from the University of St Andrews in 1986, and is still a core developer.
[src:wxwidgets/wxwidgets] On 20 February 2004, the developers of wxWindows announced that the project was changing its name to *wxWidgets*, as a result of Microsoft requesting Julian Smart to respect Microsoft's United Kingdom trademark of the term *Windows*.
[src:wxwidgets/wxwidgets] Version 3.0 was released on 11 November 2013.
[src:wxwidgets/wxwidgets] wxWidgets has participated in the Google Summer of Code since 2006.
[src:wxwidgets/wxwidgets] wxWidgets is distributed under a custom made *wxWindows Licence*, similar to the GNU Lesser General Public License (LGPL), with an exception stating that derived works in binary form may be distributed on the user's own terms.
[src:wxwidgets/wxwidgets] This license is a free software license approved by the FSF, making wxWidgets free software.
[src:wxwidgets/wxwidgets] It has been approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
[src:wxwidgets/wxwidgets] The wxWidgets library is implemented in C++, with bindings available for many commonly used programming languages.
[src:wxwidgets/wxwidgets] wxWidgets is best described as a native mode toolkit as it provides a thin abstraction to a platform's native widgets, contrary to emulating the display of widgets using graphic primitives.
[src:wxwidgets/wxwidgets] Calling a native widget on the target platform results in a more native looking interface than toolkits such as Swing (for Java), as well as offering performance and other benefits.
[src:wxwidgets/wxwidgets] The toolkit is also not restricted to GUI development, having an inter-process communication layer, socket networking functionality, and more.
[src:wxwidgets/wxwidgets] There are many Rapid Application Development (RAD) and Integrated Development Environment (IDE) tools available.
